–1130","1065–Female":"1065–Deceased","1085–1108":"1085–1108","1100–Male":"1100–Deceased","1060–1130":"1060–1130","about 1060":"about 1060","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","1096":"1096","1060":"1060","110":"1100","1106":"1106","Abt 1085":"about 1085","1100":"1100","1108":"1108","Richmond Yorkshire England":"Richmond, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Richmond, Yorkshire, England":"Richmond, Yorkshire, England","Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chamberlain","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: status name from Old French <i>chambrelain</i>, Norman French <i>cambrelanc</i>, <i>cambrelen(c)</i> ‘chamberlain’ (of ancient Germanic origin, from <i>kamer</i> ‘chamber, room’, Latin <i>camera</i> (see   Chambers  ) + the diminutive suffix <i>-(l)ing</i>). This was originally the name of an official in charge of the private chambers of his master, but is so widespread in late medieval England that it must sometimes have been used of people of more ordinary status, perhaps as a nickname for an officious or self-important person or for someone who played the role of chamberlain in a folk play, tableau, or ceremony. Compare   Chancellor   for a possible similar usage."],"variants":[{"name":"Chamberlin","meanings":["English: variant of   Chamberlain  .","French: occupational name for an official in charge of the private chambers of his master, from Old French <i>chamberlenc</i> ‘chamberlain’. See also   Chamberlain   and compare above."]},{"name":"Chambers","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>chaumbre</i> ‘room (in a house); reception room in a palace or official building’ (Old French <i>chambre</i>). It is identical in implied function with the   Chamberlain  , which denoted an official: to pay <i>in cameram</i> was to pay into the exchequer, of which the <i>camerarius</i> or chamberer was in charge. The surname also applied to clerks employed there. As the office of <i>Chamberlain</i> rose in the social scale, this term remained reserved for more humble servants of the bedchamber or private quarters.","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Les Chambres, Manche (France)."]}]},{"name":"Odo","type":"FIRST","meanings":["the Celtic name Aodh has been Anglicised into Hugh, and Latinised variously Hugo, Ædus, Ædanus, Aidus, and Odo."],"variants":[]},{"name":"the","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a variant spelling of   Ty   or a transferred use of the surname, a local name for someone who lived by a common pasture, Middle English <i>tye</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":6,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":26,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":36,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":46,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Odo the Chamberlain was born about 1060, in Richmond, Yorkshire, England. He married Mrs. Odo the Chamberlain about 1085, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1130, at the age of 71."},"et":{"about 1060–1130":"umbes 1060–1130","1065–Female":"1065–Surnud","1085–1108":"1085–1108","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1060–1130":"1060–1130","about 1060":"umbes 1060","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","1096":"1096","1060":"1060","110":"1100","1106":"1106","Abt 1085":"umbes 1085","1100":"1100","1108":"1108","Richmond Yorkshire England":"Richmond, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Richmond, Yorkshire, England":"Richmond, Yorkshire, England","Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1060–1130":"noin 1060–1130","1065–Female":"1065–Kuollut","1085–1108":"1085–1108","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1060–1130":"1060–1130","about 1060":"noin 1060","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1085":"1085","1096":"1096","1060":"1060","110":"1100","1106":"1106","Abt 1085":"noin 1085","1100":"1100","1108":"1108","Richmond Yorkshire England":"Richmond, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Richm